node.contents: Given that an ANR gets called when the UI thread is blocked for 5 seconds or more: Search where you are doing expensive, long running calls in the UI-thread, e.g. network calls. You can use [strict mode](http://developer.android.com/reference/android/os/StrictMode.html) to diagnose the problem *([here](http://android-developers.blogspot.com/2010/12/new-gingerbread-api-strictmode.html) is a small introduction)*

node.contents: Just run it in a Api9+ emulator instance. Should throw you the relevant exceptions too. If these calls are present, they are always called on every phone. Some devices are probably just faster or their network connectivity is better so that everything finishes under 5 seconds as opposed to other devices. Which makes things also to seem somewhat random because the error doesn't show on the slightly faster ones.

node.contents: It's not about stressing the phone to the max. If you enabled strict mode it will detect the problematic calls, doesn't matter if the execute in 1ms or 1 hour. You will get a Force-Close, and if you look into the logcat then, you will see a exception that tells you exactly whats wrong where (e.g. a `NetworkOnMainThreadException`). So just enabled it as described in the docs and test all the functionality of your app through.

node.contents: I'm using Smack XMPP client in a custom service, and everything goes well ... until I had some reports of ANR from android market. I've been reading a lot of Threads of StackOverflow for finding what could be the reason. I also tried to read traces and dumpstate... I finally think I've understood why is this happening and how I can reproduce it. It looks like some phone, like Galaxy S, are more sensitive than others Motorola Milestone and HTC Wildfire (I have those 3 devices). When I load on purpose loads of apps, and come back to my app, it is more likely to have ANR, and especially using maps.
